description.p:
The invention will be further described by way of example only and with reference to the accompanying figures in which:
Figure 1 is a schematic representation of FRET in cameleon indicators;
Figure 2 shows extracted premolar teeth with masked 'windows' marked on the surface thereon;
Figure 3 shows images of extracted teeth following application of acid gel and disclosing gel;
Figures 4 and 5 demonstrate the use of an image analysis programme ImageJ to determine the brightness of the area treated with acid gel and disclosing gel;
Figure 6 demonstrates the use of obelin as a disclosing composition;
Figures 7a to 7b show the results of experiments carried out on the root of a tooth with a caries;
Figures 8a and 8b show the results of experiments carried out on the dentine on a tooth;
Figures 9a to 9b show the results of experiments carried out in relation to cavity identification;
Figures 10a to 10b show the results of further experiments carried out in relation to cavity identification;
Figures 11a to 11b show the results of further experiments carried out in relation to caries identification;
Figure 12 shows images of deciduous molars with cavitated lesions (A). Figure 12a and c show images of the teeth in the light and Figure 12b and 12d show monochromatic image following application of disclosing gel;
Figure 13A shows an incisor (deciduous) with a large caries lesion (known as nursing bottle syndrome), the image of the tooth taken in the light ;
Figure 13B monochromatic image of an incisor (deciduous) with a large caries lesion (known as nursing bottle syndrome) following application of disclosing gel;
Figure 14A is an image showing the smooth surface of a molar (deciduous), the image of the tooth in the light;
Figure 14B is a monochromatic image showing the smooth surface of a molar (deciduous) following application of disclosing gel;
Figure 15A and 15B shows images of the occlusal surface of molar (permanent). Figure 15A shows an image of the tooth in the light Figure 15B shows a monochromatic image following application of disclosing gel;
Figure 16A is an image of a molar (deciduous) taken in the light;
Figure 16B shows a monochromatic image following application of disclosing gel;
Figure 16C is a graphical representation of the light generated across a lesion;
Figure 17A shows an x-ray of permanent molars;
Figure 17B shows permanent molars whose mesial surface was also investigated with x-ray then disclosing gel;
Figure 18A shows an image of a tooth that had been rinsed in deionised water and removed before being assessed;
Figure 18B shows a tooth that had been rinsed and assessed in saliva; Figure 18C shows a tooth that had been rinsed in saliva but removedbefore being assessed;
Figure 18D shows a tooth that had been incubated in saliva, removed, and rinsed in deionised water before being assessed;
Figure 19A shows supra-gingival calculus imaged following addition of disclosing solution;
Figure 19B shows sub-gingival calculus and imaged following addition of disclosing solution;
Figure 20A shows an image of the tooth in the light following application of disclosing gel; box indicates area of calculus;
Figure 20B shows a monochromatic image following application of disclosing gel; box indicates area of calculus;
Figure 21A shows images of the occlusal surface of molar (permanent) in the light prior to application of disclosing gel;
Figure 21B monochromatic image of the occlusal surface of molar (permanent) following application of disclosing gel;
Figures 22a to 22c show the results of experiments carried out in relation to dental erosion and hypersensitivity;
Figures 23a to 23c show the results of further experiments carried out in relation to dental erosion and hypersensitivity;
Figures 24a to 24c show the results of yet further experiments carried out in relation to dental erosion and hypersensitivity;
Figures 25a to 25c show the results of experiments carried out using acid etched teeth;
Figures 26a to 26d show the results of further experiments carried out using acid etched teeth;
Figures 27A and 27B are graphs showing the protective effect of saliva on the acid-treated enamel compared to deionised water;
Figure 28 is a graph showing the effects of solutions of differing pH on different levels of demineralization, as measured by a change in brightness, with solutions of lower pH generating more demineralization (more brightness); and
Figure 29 is a graph indicating that the effect of foodstuffs on demineralization of teeth can be determined using the disclosing composition and assay method of the invention.

claim.claim-text:
A kit for use in detecting demineralisation, comprising;
a) a composition comprising a ion-sensitive complex according to any of claims 1-11;
b) means for applying the composition, and
c) a detector.
